30. render proper accounting of the difference noted from the purchased and distributed food items;
31. install sound internal control mechanism in the repacking of goods to monitor the release of items for repacking and account the packed relief items to ensure that these are safeguarded from possible theft, loss and wastage;
32. require the MDRRMO or property officer to prepare reports on the inventory and monitoring of all procured and donated supplies, materials, equipment, and relief goods in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014;

33. the MSWDO submit a written explanation on the difference between the number of the target beneficiaries (8,047) and the actual beneficiaries found on the master list (8,031) and on the lapses and deficiencies enumerated in this observation;
34. require Management to establish a system in the distribution of SAP and similar cash assistance programs wherein the guidelines issued by the DSWD are followed and that proper validation and appropriate profiling of beneficiaries are performed before disbursement;
35. the amount received by the 13 job order personnel of the LGU who appeared in the master list of paid beneficiaries of the ESP be refunded.

1. Management, thru the Inventory Committee, prioritize the conduct of the physical count of all properties and submit to the Auditor the Report on Physical Count of PPE/Inventory Report to be done annually henceforth;
2. The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer be required to maintain and subsequently update the Ledger Cards and Stock and Property Cards in order that the reconciliation of the physical count against book balances can be facilitated; and
3. The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer reconcile the accounting and property records and make the necessary adjustments so that the accounts can be fairly presented in the financial statements.

26. direct the Treasurer and the Accountant to coordinate with GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth to determine the outstanding premium contributions of each employee in their records;
27. ensure that mandatory contributions are remitted in accordance with the provisions of R.A No. 8291, R.A. No. 9679, and R.A. No. 7875 as amended by R.A. No. 9241 and R.A. No. 10606 and its IRRs to avoid the incurrence of interest and penalties; and
28. provide justification for the non-remittance. Any additional interest charges and penalties that may be imposed for late remittances shall be shouldered by the responsible officers.

29. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the complete supporting documents in order to ascertain the propriety of the disbursement made;
30. Require the Municipal Accountant to verify and ascertain that payments for gasoline, oil and lubricants are duly supported with completely filled up driver’s trip tickets for proper evaluation on the propriety and reasonableness of fuel consumption;
31. Direct the vehicle drivers concerned to completely fill out the necessary data or information on the driver’s trip ticket; and
32. Ensure that meals, snacks, catering services are duly supported with activity design, menu, and attendance of barangay officials and volunteers involved in the activity.

37. render proper accounting of the difference noted from the purchased and distributed food items;
38. install sound internal control mechanism in the repacking of goods to monitor the release of items for repacking and account the packed relief items to ensure that these are safeguarded from possible theft, loss and wastage;
39. require the MDRRMO or property officer to prepare reports on the inventory and monitoring of all procured and donated supplies, materials, equipment, and relief goods in accordance with COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014; and
40. direct the Municipal Accountant to record all purchases of supplies, medicines, and relief goods for distribution in accordance with the aforementioned COA Circular.

41. the MSWDO submit a written explanation on the difference between the number of the target beneficiaries (8,047) and the actual beneficiaries found on the master list (8,031) and on the lapses and deficiencies enumerated in this observation;
42. require Management to establish a system in the distribution of SAP and similar cash assistance programs wherein the guidelines issued by the DSWD are followed and that proper validation and appropriate profiling of beneficiaries are performed before disbursement; and
43. the amount received by the 13 job order personnel of the LGU who appeared in the master list of paid beneficiaries of the ESP be refunded.

48. make sure to reflect the correct method of procurement to be indicated in the APP;
49. always indicate in the PO the appropriate mode of procurement undertaken;
50. strictly comply with the procurement process mandated by the IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and other issuances of the Government Procurement Policy Board;
51. Management submit the lacking required documents to the Office of the Auditor, and comply with the documentary requirements under COA Circular No. 2012-001 for future disbursements.
